: patronymic from the Older Scots and Middle English personal name   Herbert   (the change from <i>-er-</i> to <i>-ar-</i> was a common one in Old French and Middle English). An intrusive <i>n</i> later gave   Harbinson  ."]},{"name":"Hebard","meanings":["English (Surrey):","variant of   Herbert  , with assimilation of the first <i>r</i>. Compare   Hebb  .","variant of   Hibbert  ."]},{"name":"Harbert","meanings":["German and English: variant of   Herbert  ."]},{"name":"Herbers","meanings":["German and Dutch: patronymic from   Herbert  . It is found mainly in Lower Saxony and across the Dutch border."]},{"name":"Dickherber","meanings":["Probably a nickname for a fat person by the name of   Herbert  , of which <i>Herber</i> is a short form, or, more likely, in the north from <b>Die(c)kherber</b>, a topographic and distinguishing name for a <i>Herber</i> living by the dike, see   Dicke   2. Compare   Dickmeyer  ."]},{"name":"Hebert","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  French Armand, Andre, Emile, Normand, Jacques, Marcel, Pierre, Lucien, Michel, Gaston, Alcide, Camille.","French (<b>Hébert</b>): assimilated form of   Herbert  . Compare   Abair  ,   Abar  ,   Abare  ,   Abear  ,   Aber  ,   Eber  , and   Ebert  .","German: variant of   Heber   1."]},{"name":"Herber","meanings":["German and Dutch: variant of   Herbert  ."]},{"name":"Herbertson","meanings":["Scottish (Glasgow): patronymic from the Older Scots and Middle English personal name   Herbert  ."]},{"name":"Hebb","meanings":["English (East Yorkshire and northeast Midlands): from the Middle English personal name <i>Hebb</i>, <i>Ebb</i>, pet forms of   Herbert  ."]},{"name":"Herb","meanings":["South German: nickname for a harsh or rough person, from Middle High German <i>herb</i> ‘tart, harsh’.","German: from the personal name <i>Herpo</i>, a pet form of   Herbert  ."]}]},{"name":"Reginald","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Of Norman origin, derived from <i>Reginaldus</i>, a Latinized form of   Reynold   influenced by Latin <i>regina</i> ‘queen’. The full form is now regarded as very formal, and bearers generally shorten it to   Reg   in ordinary usage."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705190,"age":4,"year":"1290","julianDay":2192224,"title":"Jews Expelled From England","description":"After years of anti-Semitic behavior, King Edward I expelled Jews from England in 1290.","jurisdictionLevel":1},{"id":1705191,"age":29,"year":"1315","toYear":"1317","julianDay":2201354,"title":"Famine Strikes Europe","description":"A famine caused by cold winters and wet summers across Europe caused millions to die due to starvation. Desperation from hunger caused high levels of crime, stampedes in bread lines in London, infanticide, and even cannibalism throughout Europe.","jurisdictionLevel":1},{"id":1705192,"age":42,"year":"1328","julianDay":2206102,"title":"First War of Scottish Independence","description":"The First War of Scottish Independence began after England invaded Scotland in 1296. The Treaty of Edinburgh was signed in 1328 which declared peace between the two kingdoms and brought the war to an end.","jurisdictionLevel":1},{"id":1705193,"age":51,"year":"1337","toYear":"1453","julianDay":2209390,"title":"The Hundred Years' War","description":"The Hundred Years' War between France and England was largely due to the question of legitimate succession to the French crown.","jurisdictionLevel":1},{"id":1705195,"age":96,"year":"1382","julianDay":2225826,"title":"Wycliffe's Bible","description":"John Wycliffe, English theologian and professor at the University of Oxford, completed a translation of the Bible from the Latin Vulgate into Middle English. This translation is known as Wycliffe's Bible and was completed around 1382.","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wycliffe%27s_Bible","urlTitle":"Wikipedia - Wycliffe's Bible","jurisdictionLevel":1}],"lifeSummary":"When Reginald Herbert 